post_text: Mum sale to support our Choir programs.
shared_text:
Wellington High School
20 hrs ·

The Wellington Choral Boosters will be holding their annual Mum Sale September 14th through September 25th. These beautiful flowers are locally grown by Hook’s Greenhouse and come in white, orange/bronze, yellow, red/burgundy, and pink/lavender colors. We will be selling eight inch pots for $8.00 each. Contact a Wellington Choir member to purchase your mums. If, as the sale proceeds, you would like to order and a choir student does not contact you, please contact Mrs, Arcuri at 647-7411.

The flowers will be delivered by students after September 29th in time for fall planting. The proceeds from the mum sale go to benefit all the choral programs in the Wellington Schools.

Please support the Wellington choirs and BUY A MUM!

Wellington High School
September 14 at 2:20 PM ·

Parents/Guardians: a reminder that the Chromebook 1:1 technology policy must be completed BEFORE students (grades 4-12) are able to receive their Chromebook. Here is how to access the form:

1- On the school website, under "Services", click on "Technology Services"
2- On the left side of the "Technology Services" page, click on the first form (1:1 Parent Chromebook Letter)
3- In the letter, click on the 3rd blue hyperlink- "WEVSD Device Agreement". This will take your parent to the form that needs to be completed

post_text: Notice is hereby given by the Treasurer of the Wellington Exempted Village School District Board of Education that the Work Session scheduled for Tuesday, September 1, 2020 will be changed to a SPECIAL SESSION on September 1, 2020 at 6 p.m. via Zoom. The purpose of the Special Session is to have presentations and discussions on: Food and Nutrition Services, EdOptions as partner for 100% online learning and Safe Restart Family Resource Guide. The Board will take action on Edmentum and the hiring of full-time floating district substitutes teachers and tutors. The Board will move to Executive Session per the Ohio Revised Code 121.22 (G)(1); (G)(6) to consider the appointment, employment or compensation of a public employee or official; to discuss safety and security, union matters and legal matters.
text: Notice is hereby given by the Treasurer of the Wellington Exempted Village School District Board of Education that the Work Session scheduled for Tuesday, September 1, 2020 will be changed to a SPECIAL SESSION on September 1, 2020 at 6 p.m. via Zoom. The purpose of the Special Session is to have presentations and discussions on: Food and Nutrition Services, EdOptions as partner for 100% online learning and Safe Restart Family Resource Guide. The Board will take action on Edmentum and the hiring of full-time floating district substitutes teachers and tutors. The Board will move to Executive Session per the Ohio Revised Code 121.22 (G)(1); (G)(6) to consider the appointment, employment or compensation of a public employee or official; to discuss safety and security, union matters and legal matters.

The Educational Service Center of Lorain County has partnered with the Wellington Schools, Second Harvest Food Bank, and the National Guard to have a Drive-thru Food Pantry on Wednesday, Aug. 12.
It will be held at Wellington High School (629 N. Main St.).
Food distribution will occur from 3:30 to 5:30 p.m.
Second Harvest will be sending National Guard support for this event and the distribution will likely include (items vary per distribution location): assorted boxes of shelf-stable food, fresh produce, dairy boxes, baby food, frozen meat, bread, etc.

post_text:
Ohio's Sales Tax Holiday is this weekend! With all the changes going on within our schools, our supply lists are still being tweaked. You can certainly reference last year's lists (posted below) to get you started, but be aware that these may change. You may want to wait to buy big ticket items like Trapper Keepers and 3-ring binders, or hang onto those receipts to return items that are not needed.

Details on the Sales Tax Holiday can be found at: https://tax.ohio.gov/wps/portal/gov/tax/home/news/sales-tax-holiday#:~:text=Ohio%20will%20have%20a%20sales,2020%20at%2011%3A59%20p.m.&text=An%20item%20of%20school%20instructional,under%20the%20sales%20tax%20holiday.

The purpose of the Work Session will be to have a discussion with EdOptions as partner for 100% Online Learning Option and discussion on Safe Restart Family Resource Guide. The Board will move to Executive Session per the Ohio Revised Code 121.22 (G)(1); (G)(6) to consider the appointment, employment or compensation of a public employee or official; to discuss Safety and Security and to discuss Union matters. There will be no action taken.

Wellington High School
June 22 at 1:14 PM ·

From Mrs. Drake, 6/22

Good afternoon Class of 2020!

I know many of you are anxious to get your senior banner that was displayed downtown on graduation weekend. I will be in the office tonight (Monday, June 22nd) from 6 until 7 pm, and the main office will be open tomorrow (Tuesday, June 23rd) from 9 am until 1 pm if you or a family member would like to stop by to pick up your senior bag. The only item I am still waiting for is a copy of the graduation ceremony for all of you that participated in the graduation.

If you are unable to pick up your bag tonight or tomorrow, no worries, I am hoping to get enough staff members to deliver the bags either the week of June 29th or the week of July 6th.

If you have any questions, please let me know.

Thanks and take care,

Mrs. Tina Drake
Wellington High School Principal
(440) 647-7402

post_text: Congratulations! #DukePride!
shared_text:
Hans M. Schneider
May 30 at 10:52 PM ·

As the school year closes out, so does the career of band director Toni Novotny. The former WHS graduate has led the band since 1999 and made sure they were ready for every football game, basketball game, parade, concert and competition.

The signs at the village entrances proudly display the years the WHS marching band achieved a Superior rating at the state finals. Under Novotny’s direction, the band brought home state titles in 2002, 2009, 2013, 2015 and 2016.

On behalf of the Village, we thank Toni for her dedication to her craft and her students. The band always served as excellent ambassadors of both the school district and the village. Enjoy your retirement Toni!
text:
Congratulations! #DukePride!

Hans M. Schneider
May 30 at 10:52 PM ·

As the school year closes out, so does the career of band director Toni Novotny. The former WHS graduate has led the band since 1999 and made sure they were ready for every football game, basketball game, parade, concert and competition.

The signs at the village entrances proudly display the years the WHS marching band achieved a Superior rating at the state finals. Under Novotny’s direction, the band brought home state titles in 2002, 2009, 2013, 2015 and 2016.

On behalf of the Village, we thank Toni for her dedication to her craft and her students. The band always served as excellent ambassadors of both the school district and the village. Enjoy your retirement Toni!

post_text:
Today is School Lunch Hero Day, a chance to showcase the difference school nutrition professionals make for every child who comes through the cafeteria. While we may no longer be serving in our school cafeterias, our foodservice employees continue to be hard at work packaging breakfast/lunches for many families throughout our district.

Every Wednesday, meals are distributed at the back of Wellington High School. Anyone with children ages 1-18 are welcome to get a free meal. We offer five breakfast and five lunch offerings. This week we are excited to be able to offer microwave meals. This week we have a hamburger with hash brown stars and a round pizza. The staff are working hard to offer you the best tasting, most nutritious meals available.
#SchoolLunchHeroDay

THANK YOU ALL!

post_text:
#DukePride2020

Name: Nick Martinelli

High school activities: Wrestling, track, soccer, Cross Country.

Best high school memory: Nick has enjoyed finishing his high school career at Wellington and has made ever lasting friendships and grateful to the coaches

Future plans: With a strong passion to be in law enforcement, Nick became employed in the Wellington Auxiliary police department, he was then chosen to attend the Sheriff’s academy his senior year. Upon completion he will join the sheriff’s department and serve his time while awaiting to attend the Police Academy in 2021. He will attend a 2 week study course with the FBI in June, while employed at Cedar Point as security and will then plan to attend LCCC in the fall of 2020 to support his law enforcement dreams.

Good Afternoon Wellington Families!

This is Chad Heileman, after school and 21st Century Program Director with Boys and Girls Club.

This is an important update from the Boys and Girls Clubs of Northeast Ohio. If you have an internet connected device in your home, Boys and Girls Club now offers fun, interactive programming on line that can be accessed in the safety of your own home. Simply go to www.bgcneo.org and click on Cyber Club. Cyber Club offers activities, videos, and games centered around Character and Citizenship, Sports and Recreation, The Arts, and Education. All programming is introduced to you by our very own staff, so you may even see some familiar faces! Everything is free and a lot of fun. We miss serving you and your children very much and we can't wait to get back to our regular programming. In the meantime, stay home, stay safe, and feel free to check us out at www.bgcneo.org by clicking on Cyber Club.

post_text:
UPDATE sent to families via email tonight, Monday, April 13.

Good evening Wellington School District Families,

This is Superintendent Weber with an update on our meal service plan for this week. Although our schools are on Spring Break, we will continue our meal service program with pick-up on Wednesday with the same hours as last week. The morning time will be from 9 until 11 and the afternoon time from 4 until 6. We will continue to use the doors behind the high school for distribution. This food service is available to all families and 10 meals per child can be picked up for children age 3 through 18.

Thank you for your partnership with the Wellington Schools and have a good week ahead, stay safe and healthy.

Sincerely,
Edward Weber

post_text: A message from McCormick Middle School (March 26, 2020).
shared_text:
Mccormick Middle School
March 26 at 10:09 AM ·

NOTE: Because of the news of a verified case of COVID-19 in Wellington, Mr. Baxendale is cancelling tomorrow’s work pick-up/drop off. He will send out new guidance on Sunday. Sorry for any inconvenience.

Good Morning McCormick Families,

Due to the conflicts that many families face preventing them from coming to school during normal hours I will be at McCormick on Saturday March 28, 2020 from 10:00am to 2:00pm. During this time I will be collecting completed work, passing out additional work you may need and allowing for pick up of essential personal items from student lockers. If you simply need to drop off completed work you can do so in the crate which will be located in the vestibule. If you have any other needs please e-mail me ASAP at nbaxendale@wellingtonvillageschools.org so I can schedule an appointment time. This process will provide adherence to the recommended social diistancing practices.

Thank you all for your continued patience and support and have a great day.

Mr. Baxendale

post_text:
UPDATE sent to families via email Sunday, March 22.

Dear Wellington School District Families,
Thank you for all your cooperation and coordination with our schools during this underrepresented past week. Given the Governor's orders today to shelter in place as much as possible, we are moving our food service program to once a week, where you can pick up 10 meals per child. This is available for all Wellington families. Our new meal pick up times will be Wednesday's from 3:00 PM until 6:00 PM. Please remain in your car and wait for our service staff to deliver curbside behind the high school. For those already planning on meal pick up tomorrow, We will be open on Monday, with breakfast service from 7:30 until 8:30 and lunch service from 11:30 until 12:30, but then it will be Wednesday's only from 3:00 PM until 6:00 PM. Please practice social distancing and stay healthy and safe. Good evening, and thank you for your partnership with the Wellington Schools.

post_text:
UPDATE from Mr. Weber sent via email to families (Wednesday, March 18, 2020)

Dear Wellington Families,
Thank you for all your coordination with our schools during this COVID-19 shutdown period. We are grateful for your partnership. We have heard feedback from some families requesting an evening food service option and we have been able to make that happen. Each Thursday evening during the shutdown we will have an evening pick-up option behind the high school from 5:00 PM until 6:00 PM.

Here is our serving hours:

Monday through Friday
Breakfast service from 7:30-8:30
Lunch service from 11:30-12:30

Thursday Evenings
Dinner service from 5:00-6:00

For each student, 5 breakfasts and 5 lunches can be picked up at one time for a whole week supply. The pickup location is behind the high school at the dining room doors. Remember, this service is available for all families within our school district. Please make sure to follow all the guidelines from our health department to keep our community as safe as possible. Thank you!

Mccormick Middle School
March 17 at 5:20 PM ·

Good Evening McCormick Middle School Families,

I want to first thank each and everyone of you for your support and patience during this unexpected event. I also want to share my gratitude for all of the dedication of you families and the teachers to give our students a continuity of education. We will all come through this event as a stronger McCormick family. Effective at 5pm on Tuesday March 17, 2020, McCormick Middle School will be closed to the public until further notice. Any questions or concerns that you may have can be directed to your children's teachers or to me at nbaxendale@wellingtonvillageschools.org.
I encourage each of you to adhere to the guidelines that are being set nationwide so we can return to normalcy safely and quickly. Our thoughts are with all of you and do not hesitate to reach out with anything you may need.

Sincerely,

Nathan Baxendale

post_text: Sharing this info on behalf of Village officials.
shared_text:
Village of Wellington, Ohio
March 16 at 1:18 PM ·

Village of Wellington Residents

During this COVID-19 virus outbreak people will be increasing their cleaning and disinfection at work and home. Please be reminded that disinfecting wipes, baby wipes and other types of wipes are banned from disposal to the Village of Wellington's sewer collection system and to the Waste Water Treatment Plant. These items are not able to be broken down or pumped and will create back-up conditions out in the sewer collection system which will cause back-ups in homes and businesses.

Thank you for your cooperation.

post_text:
The Wellington Schools Endowment Fund was started to provide funding for non-required school programs like the performing arts, athletics and extra-curricular activities. Donations to the Endowment are never spent, but a percentage of the investment income is returned to fund teacher grants, scholarships, and a match for Wellington Student's College 529 Savings Plans. The Endowment has returned over $800,000 to benefit Wellington students. Nearly every student attending Wellington schools has participated in programs or activities sponsored by the Endowment.

To learn more, visit the Wellington School's web page and click on the Endowment link. https://www.wellingtonvillageschools.org/Page/1521

From Mr. Weber:
Dear Wellington Schools Community, here is the guidelines given to our schools today, Tuesday, March 10, from the Ohio Department of Health. Please make sure that your child's teacher has your most up to date contact information. The health department could possibly ask us to close in the future. We are making contingency plans for the continuation of our instructional and meal service programs if this need occurs. Thank you for your continued partnership with the Wellington Schools.

There are many places to get your questions answered straight from district admins regarding our district and Issue 16. We invite residents to attend, bring a friend, ask questions, and learn about how Issue 16 supports students now and for years to come. Dates and times are:

Tuesday, March 10 from 6 to 7:30 p.m. Open House and Tour at Westwood Elementary School, 305 Union Street.

Thursday, March 12 at 8 a.m. the annual State of Wellington Address at the Wellington Eagles #205, 631 Main Street, Tickets are $10 for the breakfast portion of the event.

Saturday, March 14, from 8:30 to 10:30 a.m. Dialogue with the Board of Education at Bread & Brew, 100 S Main Street

If you still have questions regarding Issue 16, we encourage you to watch an informational Dialogue with the Dukes video regarding Issue 16 produced by our very own Wellington High School students from the Digital Media class at WHS. post_text: Join us!
shared_text:
Wellington Kiwanis
February 26 at 5:44 PM ·

Wellington Kiwanis Club is sponsoring its third annual “State of Wellington” Breakfast, featuring our village and school leaders, at 8 a.m., Thursday, March 12, at the Wellington Eagles, 631 St. Main St. Wellington.

Keynote speakers will be Wellington Schools’ Superintendent Ed Weber and Treasurer Tina Gabler and Mayor Hans Schneider, and Village Manager Steve Dupee. Weber will discuss the need for the upcoming permanent improvement levy and bond issue that will be on the March 17 ballot while Gabler will provide a district financial update. Schneider and Dupee will focus on 2019 village highlights and upcoming projects/activities in 2020 including an update on the new police station and Union School Park.

Tickets are $10. They can be purchased at the Mayor’s Office on the third floor of the Town Hall; Bremke Insurance, 104 S. Main St.; Fifth Third Bank, 161 E. Herrick Ave.; and Main Street Wellington, 118 W. Herrick Ave. Tickets must be purchased by Saturday, March 7. The buffet breakfast will be served by the Fraternal Order of Eagles.

post_text:
Several Lorain County JVS students, including Wellington High School junior, Jessica Davis, will be advancing to the State SkillsUSA Competition in Columbus to be held in April. These JVS students earned this honor by receiving top ratings in the North Central Regional SkillsUSA Competitions held recently at the Ohio Carpenters’ Joint Apprenticeship & Training Center (Richfield), Medina County Career Center (Medina) and Ohio Technical College (Cleveland).

Jessica, a Carpentry student, received a gold in the Customer Service event.

SkillsUSA is a career-technical youth club comprised of students, teachers and industry, working together to ensure that America has a skilled workforce.

Congratulations and Good Luck! #DukePride
text:
Several Lorain County JVS students, including Wellington High School junior, Jessica Davis, will be advancing to the State SkillsUSA Competition in Columbus to be held in April. These JVS students earned this honor by receiving top ratings in the North Central Regional SkillsUSA Competitions held recently at the Ohio Carpenters’ Joint Apprenticeship & Training Center (Richfield), Medina County Career Center (Medina) and Ohio Technical College (Cleveland).

Jessica, a Carpentry student, received a gold in the Customer Service event.

SkillsUSA is a career-technical youth club comprised of students, teachers and industry, working together to ensure that America has a skilled workforce.

Congratulations and Good Luck! #DukePride

post_text:
A success story from The Wellington Endowment Fund!

Check out the February 20th Wellington Enterprise in The Lorain County Community Guide newspaper to learn more about the exciting vertical garden projects at the High School, brought to you by the generous support of the Wellington Endowment Fund and THRIVE! Southern Lorain County (powered by the United Way.)

The Wellington Schools Endowment Fund was started to provide funding for non-required school programs like the performing arts, athletics and extra-curricular activities. The Endowment distributes funds to Wellington students in three ways: through teacher grants, scholarships and a college 529 match program. The vertical garden project was part of a teacher grant.

https://issuu.com/loraincountyprinting/docs/lcg_02202020/14

post_text:
A message from the Superintendent's office:

Please attend one of the open houses next week to learn about the Improvement Bonds and Maintenance Levy that our schools need.

Tuesday, February 25 @ Westwood Elementary School @ 6:00-7:30 PM

Thursday, February 27 @ Wellington High School @ 6:00-7:30 PM

Our schools are seeking a 1.89 Mill Bond and a 1 Mill Maintenance Levy to support the needs of our aging schools, Westwood Elementary School (70 years old) and Wellington High School (50 years old).

The cost of this new levy is $8.43 per month (per $100,000 of home valuation)

Thank you for all your support to keep up the progress our schools are making!
